'' ''1,626''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1920 United States presidential election|1920]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|22.7% ''440''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''77.3%''' ''1,501''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1916 United States presidential election|1916]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|10.6% ''159''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''88.6%''' ''1,326''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.8% ''12''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1912 United States presidential election|1912]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|3.0% ''40''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''80.0%''' ''1,061''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|17.0% ''225''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==Education==\nThe parish is served by the [[Tangipahoa Parish School System]].<ref>[http://www.tangischools.org/  Official website] of the [[Tangipahoa Parish School System]]</ref> [[Southeastern Louisiana University]] is located in [[Hammond, Louisiana|Hammond]].\n\nOn seven occasions, the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] has sued the Tangipahoa Parish School Board, along with other defendants, for having allegedly sponsored and promoted religion in teacher-led school activities.<ref>Mitchell, David. \"School board sued over prayer\", ''[[The Advocate (Baton Rouge)|Baton Rouge Morning Advocate]]'', Capital City Press, p. B01.{{When|date=May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===School Board===\nThe elected school board governs and oversees the Tangipahoa Parish School System (TPSS). The board appoints the superintendent of schools, who leads the school system and oversees is functioning. The current superintendent is Melissa M. Stilley. The president of the board is Sandra Bailey-Simmons, and the vice president is Tom Tolar.\n\nMelissa M. Stilley, superintendent\n\nJanice Fultz Richards (D), District A\n\nTom Tolar (R), District B\n\nRobin Abrams (R), District C\n\nGlenn Westmoreland (R), District D\n\nBrett Duncan (I), District E\n\nRandy Bush (R), District F\n\nJerry Moore (D), District G\n\nSandra Bailey-Simmons (R), District H\n\nRose Quave Dominguez (R), District I\n\nThe Board has a long history of racial discrimination in the hiring of teachers. In 1975, it was ordered to ensure one-third of the teaching staff were Black. Both the Board and the Court ignored the mandate for more than thirty years. During the period from 1998 to 2008, the Board hired fewer Black teachers than any other school system in the state. In 2010, a second ruling strengthened the first.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Anderson |first1=Melinda |title=A Root Cause of the Teacher-Diversity Problem |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2018/01/a-root-cause-of-the-teacher-diversity-problem/551234/ |accessdate=21 August 2018 |magazine=The Atlantic |date=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==National Guard==\nThe parish is home to the [[204th Theater Airfield Operations Group]] and the Forward Support Company of the 205th Engineer Battalion.  This 205th Engineer Battalion is a component of the [[225th Engineer Brigade]] of the [[Louisiana National Guard]].  These units reside within the city of [[Hammond, Louisiana|Hammond]]. A detachment of the 1021st Engineer Company (Vertical) resides in [[Independence, Louisiana]].  The [[236th Combat Communications Squadron]] of the [[Louisiana Air National Guard]] also resides at the Hammond Airport.\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Map of Tangipahoa Parish Louisiana With Municipal Labels.PNG|thumb|180px|right|Map of Tangipahoa Parish, depicting municipal boundaries]]\n\n=== Cities ===\n\n* [[Hammond, Louisiana|Hammond]] (largest municipality)\n* [[Ponchatoula, Louisiana|Ponchatoula]]\n\n===Towns===\n* [[Amite City, Louisiana|Amite City]] (parish seat)\n* [[Independence, Louisiana|Independence]]\n* [[Kentwood, Louisiana|Kentwood]]\n* [[Roseland, Louisiana|Roseland]]\n\n===Villages===\n* [[Tangipahoa, Louisiana|Tangipahoa]]\n* [[Tickfaw, Louisiana|Tickfaw]]\n\n===Census-designated place===\n* [[Natalbany, Louisiana|Natalbany]]\n\n===Other unincorporated places===\n{{div col}}\n* [[Baptist, Louisiana|Baptist]]\n* [[Fluker, Louisiana|Fluker]]\n* [[Husser, Louisiana|Husser]]\n* [[Loranger, Louisiana|Loranger]]\n* [[Manchac, Louisiana|Manchac]] (Akers)\n* [[Pumpkin Center, Louisiana|Pumpkin Center]]\n* [[Robert, Louisiana|Robert]]\n* [[Rosaryville, Louisiana|Rosaryville]]\n* [[Wilmer, Louisiana|Wilmer]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Chris Broadwater]], current District 86 state representative, resides in Hammond\n* [[Nick Bruno]], president of [[University of Louisiana at Monroe]]\n* [[Hodding Carter]], 20th-century journalist\n* [[William Hodding Carter, I]], politician; father of Hodding Carter\n* [[John L. Crain]], president of [[Southeastern Louisiana University]]\n* [[John Desmond]], architect\n* [[John Bel Edwards]], current [[Governor of Louisiana]]; former Minority Leader of [[Louisiana House of Representatives]]; former District 72 state representative, resides in [[Amite City, Louisiana|Amite]]\n* [[Lucy Fleming]], singer\n* [[C. B. Forgotston]], political activist\n* [[Barbara Forrest]], critic of [[intelligent design]]\n* [[Tim Gautreaux]], writer\n* [[Dennis Paul Hebert]], state representative for Tangipahoa Parish, 1972-1996<ref>{{cite news|url=http://obits.theadvocate.com/obituaries/theadvocate/obituary.aspx?n=dennis-p-hebert&pid=175822744&fhid=17442|title=Dennis P. Hebert|newspaper=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Baton Rouge Advocate]]|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Bolivar E. Kemp]], U.S. representative, 1925\u20131933\n* [[Bolivar Edwards Kemp, Jr.]], [[Louisiana Attorney General]], 1948\u20131952\n* [[Wade Miley]], professional baseball pitcher \n* [[James H. Morrison]], represented [[Louisiana's 6th congressional district]] from 1943 to 1967\n* [[Kim Mulkey]], college basketball player, United States Olympic Team, Baylor head women's basketball coach\n* [[Rufus Porter (American football)|Rufus Porter]], professional football player \n* [[Henry \"Tank\" Powell]], state representative from 1996 to 2008\n* [[Steve Pugh (Louisiana politician)|Steve Pugh]], state representative since 2008\n* [[Billy Reid (fashion designer)|Billy Reid]], fashion designer\n* [[Beth Rickey]], political activist who opposed [[David Duke]] and taught for a time at Southeastern Louisiana University<ref>Patricia Sullivan, \"Beth Rickey dies with an immune disorder and Crohn's disease,\" ''[[Washington Post]]'', September 16, 2009</ref>\n* [[Weldon Russell]], former state representative from Tangipahoa and St. Helena parishes\n* [[Britney Spears]], singer\n* [[Jackie Smith]], former professional football player, St. Louis Cardinals and [[Dallas Cowboys]], NFL Hall of Famer\n* [[Irma Thomas]], [[Grammy]]-winning singer\n* [[Harry Wilson (Louisiana politician)|Harry D. Wilson]], Louisiana state representative and state agriculture commissioner; pushed for the establishment of the town of Independence in 1912\n* [[Justin Wilson (chef)|Justin Wilson]], chef and humorist\n* [[Robert Alford (American football)|Robert Alford]], professional football player, [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n* [[Harlan Miller]], professional football player, [[Arizona Cardinals]]\n* [[Kevin Hughes (American football)|Kevin Hughes]], professional football player, [[St. Louis Rams]] and [[Carolina Panthers]]\n* [[Donald Dykes]], former professional football player, [[New York Jets]] and [[San Diego Chargers]]\n*[[Ronald Caruso]], former mayor of Tickfaw\n* [[Earl Wilson (baseball)|Earl Wilson]], former major league baseball player for [[Boston Red Sox]], [[Detroit Tigers]] and [[San Diego Padres]]\n* [[LaBrandon Toefield]], former professional football player, [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] and [[Carolina Panthers]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Tangipahoa Parish, Louisiana]]\n* [[Tangipahoa Parish Sheriff's Office (Louisiana)|Tangipahoa Parish Sheriff's Office]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* [http://www.tangipahoa.org/ Tangipahoa Parish official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150927062618/http://www.tangi-cvb.org/site49.php Tangipahoa Parish history], on the Convention and Visitors Bureau website\n* {{cite web| url=http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/louisiana/ | title=Explore the History and Culture of Southeastern Louisiana | publisher=[[National Park Service]] | work=Discover Our Shared Heritage Travel Itinerary}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Center    = Tangipahoa Parish, Louisiana\n|North     = [[Pike County, Mississippi]]\n|Northeast = [[Walthall County, Mississippi]]\n|East      = [[Washington Parish, Louisiana|Washington Parish]] and [[St. Tammany Parish, Louisiana|St. Tammany Parish]] \n|Southeast = [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]]\n|South     = [[St. Charles Parish, Louisiana|St. Charles Parish]]\n|Southwest = [[St. John the Baptist Parish, Louisiana|St. John the Baptist Parish]]\n|West      = [[St. Helena Parish, Louisiana|St. Helena Parish]] and [[Livingston Parish, Louisiana|Livingston Parish]] \n|Northwest = [[Amite County, Mississippi]]\n}}\n\n{{Tangipahoa Parish, Louisiana}}\n{{Louisiana parishes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Coord|30.63|-90.40|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-LA_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n[[Category:Louisiana parishes]]\n[[Category:Tangipahoa Parish, Louisiana| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1869]]\n[[Category:Southeastern Louisiana University]]\n[[Category:Swamps of Louisiana]]\n[[Category:1869 establishments in Louisiana]]\n", "name_user": "Whoisjohngalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "