{"title_page": "Joseph S. Pulver Sr.", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image       = Joseph_S._Pulver,_Sr.jpg\n| imagesize   = 250px\n| name        = Joseph S. Pulver Sr.\n| caption     =\n| pseudonym   =\n| birth_date  = 1955\n| birth_place = Schenectady, New York\n| death_date  = 21 april 2020\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = Writer, poet, editor\n| nationality = United States\n| period      =\n| genre       = [[Horror fiction]], [[noir fiction]], [[hardboiled]], [[dark fantasy]], poetry\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| signature   =\n| website     = {{URL|http://thisyellowmadness.wordpress.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Joseph S. Pulver''' Sr. (1955 \u2013 April 21, 2020) was an author and poet, much of whose work falls within the [[horror fiction]], [[noir fiction]] / [[hardboiled]], and [[dark fantasy]] genres. He lived in Germany.\n\n== Work as author ==\nPulver started his publishing career in the early 1990s with a number of short stories published in various American [[small press]] magazines, foremost among them [[Robert M. Price]]'s ''Crypt of [[Cthulhu]]''. His tales cover subjects ranging from [[Robert Wiene]]'s ''[[The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari]]'' to [[H.P. Lovecraft]]'s [[Cthulhu Mythos]] and [[Robert W. Chambers]]' \"[[King in Yellow]].\"\n\nPulver's professional debut came with the publication of his [[Lovecraftian]] novel, \"[[Nightmare's Disciple]]\".\n\nIn addition to various American [[small press]] magazines ([[Hippocampus Press]], [[Lovecraft eZine]], [[Nemonymous]], etc.). Pulver's work has been featured in numerous [[anthologies]] in the US, UK, France, and Japan. Some of these [[anthologies]] include: \"Black Wings: New Tales of Lovecraftian Horror\", \"The Tindalos Mythos\", \"Spawn of the Green Abyss\", \"The Book of Eibon\", [[Lin Carter]]'s \"Anton Zarnak: Supernatural Sleuth\", and \"Rehearsals For Oblivion\".\n\nNearly two dozen short works of his have been translated into French and Japanese.\n\n== Work as editor ==\nPulver has also been the editor of [[Midnight Shambler]] and Tales of Lovecraftian Horror. He was also the co-editor for [[Crypt of Cthulhu]], published by Mythos Books LLC working alongside [[Robert M. Price]], [[Michael Cisco]] and David Wynn.\n\nHe has also edited collections by [[Ann K. Schwader]] (The Worms Remember, Hive Press) and John B. Ford (Dark Shadows on the Moon, Hive Press).\n\nIn 2012 Pulver edited ''A Season in Carcosa'' (an anthology of new tales based on [[Robert W. Chambers]]' \"[[The King in Yellow]]\" tales) for Miskatonic River Press. A year later he edited the award-winning anthology ''The Grimscribe's Puppets'' (a tribute anthology to [[Thomas Ligotti]] for the same publisher).\n\nMr. Pulver was guest editor for the [[Lovecraft eZine]] ''[[The King in Yellow]]'' special issue, which was published in April 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lovecraftzine.com/magazine/issues/2014-2/issue-30-april-2014/ |title=Introduction to Issue #30 |date=April 5, 2014 |website=lovecraftzine.com |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Cassilda's Song'' ([[Chaosium]]), an anthology based on [[Robert W. Chambers]]'s [[King in Yellow]] with new tales, written by female writers. The anthology has been released in 2015 in electronic format and will be available in print in the first quarter of 2016.\n\nFor the [[Necronomicon Providence]] Mr. Pulver edited a Round Robin for the Lovecraft Arts & Sciences Council, that included stories, artwork and accounts by participants of the [[Necronomicon Providence]] in 2013 and 2015.\n\nIn 2016 and 2017 several anthologies that have been edited by Joseph S. Pulver will be published. Amongst them are ''The Madness of Dr. Caligari'' ([[Fedogan & Bremer]], 2016), ''Darker Companions'' - a tribute to [[Ramsey Campbell]], co-edited with Scott David Aniolowski ([[PS Publishing]], 2016), ''Born under a Bad Sign'' and ''The Leaves of a Necronomicon'' ([[Chaosium]] in 2016/2017).\n\nMr. Pulver has curated the release of the [[Michael Cisco]] novella ''Knife Dance'' for Dim Shores. The novella will be published in 2016.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* 2013 [[Shirley Jackson Award]], as editor for Superior Work in an Anthology. ''The Grimscribe's Puppets'' ([[Miskatonic River Press]])\n* 2013 [[Bram Stoker Award]], Finalist for award in Superior Achievement in the Anthology Category. ''The Grimscribe's Puppets'' ([[Miskatonic River Press]])\n* 2016 [[World Fantasy Award]], Finalist for World Fantasy Award for Best Anthology. ''Cassilda's Song'' ([[Chaosium]])\n* 2016 [[Shirley Jackson Award]] nominee, for edited anthology. ''The Madness of Dr. Caligari'' ([[Fedogan & Bremer]])\n\n==Publications==\n===as editor===\n* ''The Worms remember'' by [[Ann K. Schwader]], Hive Press, 2001\n* ''Dark Shadows on the Moon'' by John B. Ford, Hive Press, 2001\n* ''A Season in Carcosa'', Miskatonic River Press, 2012\n* ''The Grimscribe's Puppets'', Miskatonic River Press, 2013\n* ''Cassilda's Song'', [[Chaosium]], 2015\n* ''The Doom that came to Providence'', The Lovecraft Arts & Sciences Council, 2015\n* ''Darker Companions'', [[PS Publishing]], co-edited with Scott D. Aniolowski, forthcoming in 2016\n* ''The Leaves of a Necronomicom'', [[Chaosium]], forthcoming in 2016\n* ''The Madness of Dr. Caligari'', [[Fedogan & Bremer]], forthcoming in 2016\n* ''Born under a Bad Sign'', [[Chaosium]], forthcoming in 2016/2017\n\n===Novels===\n* ''Nightmare's Disciple'', [[Chaosium]] 1999\n* ''The Orphan Palace'', [[Ch\u00f4mu Press]], October 2011\n\n===Collections===\n*''Blood Will Have Its Season'', edited by [[S.T. Joshi]], [[Hippocampus Press]] 2009\n*''SIN & ashes'', edited by [[S.T. Joshi]], [[Hippocampus Press]] 2010\n*''Portraits of Ruin'', [[Hippocampus Press]] 2012\n*''A House of Hollow Wounds'', edited by [[Jeffrey Thomas (writer)|Jeffrey Thomas]], [[Hippocampus Press]] 2015\n*''The Protocols of Ugliness'', (forthcoming) 2015\n*''The King in Yellow Tales, Vol. 1'', [[Lovecraft eZine]] books\n'''Graphic Novels'''\n* Knots, Gestures and Positions in [https://ashpure.com/outsideanthology/ Outside] An anthology of new horror fiction with artist Kim Bo Yung. Published by [https://ashpure.com/home/ Ash Pure] and Topic Press.\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[Anna Tambour]]: \"In human terms, if I had to compare him to other authors, I would say that he reminds me more of a mug of hot Lear blended with Cummings, served with a squeeze of post-enema'd Shelley.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://medlarcomfits.blogspot.com.au/ |first=Anna |last=Tambour |title=upcoming in A Season in Carcosa, editor: Joseph S. Pulver Sr. |date=January 24, 2012 |website=Medlar Comfits |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===''Blood Will Have Its Season''===\n\"The prose of Joe Pulver can take its place with that of the masters of our genre-Poe, Lovecraft, Campbell, Ligotti-while his imaginative reach is something uniquely his own.\" \u2014 From [[S. T. Joshi]]'s Foreword.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.blood\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/blood-will-have-its-season-by-joseph-s.-pulver-sr |title=Blood Will Have Its Season by Joseph S. Pulver Sr |first=Boyd |last=Pearson |website=Hippocampus Press |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"In this innovative, hypnotic collection, Joseph S. Pulver Sr. has proven himself to be a perversely masterful sculptor of our dreams.\"-Jeffrey Thomas.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.blood\"/>\n\n\"Joe Pulver is a dark star in the merciless cosmos of weird fiction. His work is as brutal as it is beautiful.\" \u2014 [[Wilum Pugmire]].<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.blood\"/>\n\n\"In an earlier day I feel sure Joe Pulver would have been arrested for writing some of the stuff in this collection. Maybe he will be yet! How can he write, with such intricate delicacy, thunderous prose that fairly rips up the pages it is printed on? I wish I knew!\" \u2014 [[Robert M. Price]].<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.blood\"/>\n\n===''The Grimscribe's Puppets''===\n\"[[Thomas Ligotti]] is beyond doubt one of the Grandmasters of Weird Fiction. In The Grimscribe's Puppets, Joseph S. Pulver Sr. has commissioned both new and established talents in the world of weird fiction and horror to contribute all new tales that pay homage to Ligotti and celebrate his eerie and essential nightmares. [[Poppy Z. Brite]] once asked, \"Are you out there, Thomas Ligotti?\" This anthology proves not only is he alive and well, but his extraordinary illuminations have proven to be a visionary and fertile source of inspiration for some of today's most accomplished authors.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.miskatonicriverpress.com/products/gp.shtml |title=The Grimscribe's Puppets edited by Joseph S. Pulver Sr. |website=Miskatonic River Press |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310213923/http://www.miskatonicriverpress.com/products/gp.shtml |archivedate=March 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''The Orphan Palace''===\n[[Maureen Kincaid Speller]] for ''Weird Fiction Review'': \"Moving to the present day, ''The Orphan Palace'' by Joseph S. Pulver (Ch\u00f4mu Press, 2011) certainly cannot be accused of such reticence. Ostensibly, the story of a road trip made by a serial arsonist and killer, from the West Coast to the East, in search of his childhood nemesis is not promising material, and I don't mind admitting that The Orphan Palace initially seemed to sit far out on the edge of my reading comfort zone. However, it quickly became clear that there is much more to this novel than a trail of dumped cars, torched buildings and broken and bloody bodies.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://weirdfictionreview.com/2012/03/the-mere-touch-weird-reviews/ |title=The Mere Touch: Weird Reviews |first=Maureen Kincaid |last=Speller |work=Weird Fiction Review |date=March 16, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===''Portraits of Ruin''===\n[[Matt Cardin]]: \"Just be prepared for a ride that will upend your sensibilities. [...] Portraits of Ruin truly is a Coney Island of the Mind. But it's one where the rides drip with darkness and tilt at non-Euclidean angles, and whirl you into an abyss of strange entity that grins and chitters and babbles in alien tongues (which eventually come to sound like your own voice).\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teemingbrain.com/2012/03/26/on-learning-to-read-joe-pulvers-portraits-of-ruin-by-writing-the-introduction-to-it/ |first=Matt |last=Cardin |title=On learning to read Joe Pulver\u2019s \u2018Portraits of Ruin\u2019 by writing the introduction to it |date=March 26, 2012 |website=The Teeming Brain |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Let us posit that Bukowski is the sun. Or Brautigan, Burroughs and the Beats\u2014a solar Coney Island of the Mind where Timothy Leary's dead and dead Cthulhu waits and sings the live long daydream believer. Then Joe Pulver's Portraits of Ruin would be the burst of planets, Big Bang-Bang, Marquee Moons hanging on for what they got, scream of consciousness\u2014in Outer Space no one can hear it . . . except Coffin Joe, Monster Mash Potato that big ol' Portraits of Ruin\u2014Mars needs it, you need it, so just open the lid and shake your fist\u2014then say: \"They kill horses, horses, horses, horses.\" Thank you. Come again?\" \u2014Thomas Ligotti.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.portraits\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/portraits-of-ruin |title=Portraits of Ruin by Joseph S. Pulver Sr. |first=Boyd |last=Pearson |website=Hippocampus Press |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Fearless. Daring. Poetic prose for the unhinged. Each tale in Portraits of Ruin packs the sort of mental wallop that leaves the reader reeling. From the scorched deserts to the highest foreign towers, across plains of reality and beneath burning suns, this is no volume for the weak, for the conventional. It is a wake-up call from one of the genre's most visionary masters. A book for those who see differently, for those not afraid to know the truth no matter how terrible the cost. I envy anyone about to experience Pulver's horrors for the first time.\" \u2013 [[Simon Strantzas]], author of ''Nightingale Songs''.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.portraits\"/>\n\n===''A Season in Carcosa''===\n[[Nic Pizzolatto]], the creator of ''[[True Detective (TV series)|True Detective]]'', refers to ''A Season in Carcosa'' in a recent interview with ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/02/02/writer-nic-pizzolatto-on-thomas-ligotti-and-the-weird-secrets-of-true-detective/ |title=Writer Nic Pizzolatto on Thomas Ligotti and the Weird Secrets of 'True Detective' |first=Michael |last=Calia |date=February 2, 2014 |journal=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> \"For fans of the show who'd like to see what contemporary voices have done with Chambers' \"King in Yellow,\" I'd point them toward Karl Edward Wagner's short story \"The River of Night's Dreaming\" or the recent anthology \"A Season in Carcosa.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/5-things-we-learned-from-true-detective-20140310 |title=5 Things We Learned From 'True Detective' |first=David |last=Fear |date=March 10, 2014 |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Walter Hicks]] (Hellbound Times): \"This is a superior collection, with a diverse and outstanding line-up of talent. As with any anthology, some of the stories will work better for individual readers than others, but each one merits inclusion and consideration here. Does it accentuate the reading experience to be familiar with Chambers/The King in Yellow? Probably, and though I would highly recommend reading the source material, it certainly is not a necessity. All readers who enjoy ominous, enigmatic and darkly beautiful literature, highly imaginative journeys into madness, altered realities and the true terror behind the Mask will relish spending A Season in Carcosa.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Season-Carcosa-Sr-Joseph-Pulver/dp/1937408000/ref=wl_it_dp_o_pdT1_nS_nC?ie=UTF8&colid=2F4V4U3J4GAY8&coliid=I2K4OSCSYV1Q9D |title=A Season in Carcosa |editor-first=Joseph S. |editor-last=Pulver Sr. |date=September 15, 2012 |publisher=Miskatonic River Press, LLC |accessdate=June 15, 2017 |via=Amazon}}</ref>\n\n===SIN & ashes===\nLaird Barron in SF Signal: \"Joe Pulver's Sin & Ashes is a hardboiled/noir/horror collection that reads like prose poetry; a psychedelic hybrid of James Ellroy, William Burroughs, and H.P. Lovecraft. It'll rattle your brain.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sfsignal.com/archives/2010/12/be-my-victim-laird-barron |title=Be My Victim: A Discussion with Laird Barron on Literary Horror and Anti-Intellectualism |work=SF Signal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013093326/http://www.sfsignal.com/archives/2010/12/be-my-victim-laird-barron/ |archivedate=October 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"Joseph S Pulver Sr. is a thunderous scribe of dark fiction. His poetry slams into you, cracking through flesh and bone to the real meat beneath. SIN & ashes is his mighty hammer, deftly wielded and smithed on Hephaestus's great anvil. This is no book for the faint of heart. Filled with hard boiled goodness and devastating imagery, Pulver proves his is a talent to be reckoned with, and cements his rightful place as one of the most interesting voices in the genre. I am both awed and humbled by his power.\" \u2014 Simon Strantzas.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.portraits\"/>\n\n\"Joe Pulver's ''Sins and Ashes'' is a messed up (and I mean Cronenberg messed up) splicing of William S. Burroughs and Thomas Ligotti. Add a whiskey chaser. After reading these vibrant and weird stories with their assorted devils and down-and-outs, I kinda want to party with Joe. But I think I'm too scared to.\" \u2014 Paul Tremblay, author of The Little Sleep and in the Mean Time.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.portraits\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{isfdb name}}\n*{{facebook|jspulver}}\n*[http://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/sin-ashes-by-joseph-s.-pulver-sr. \"SIN & ashes\" at Hippocampus Press]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pulver, Joseph S. Sr.}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cthulhu Mythos writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American book editors]]\n[[Category:American horror writers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Berlin]]\n[[Category:American male short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Weird fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Schenectady, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image       = Joseph_S._Pulver,_Sr.jpg\n| imagesize   = 250px\n| name        = Joseph S. Pulver Sr.\n| caption     =\n| pseudonym   =\n| birth_date  = 1955\n| birth_place = Schenectady, New York\n| death_date  = 21 april 2020\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = Writer, poet, editor\n| nationality = United States\n| period      =\n| genre       = [[Horror fiction]], [[noir fiction]], [[hardboiled]], [[dark fantasy]], poetry\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| signature   =\n| website     = {{URL|http://thisyellowmadness.wordpress.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Joseph S. Pulver''' Sr. (1955 \u2014 April 21, 2020) was an author and poet, much of whose work falls within the [[horror fiction]], [[noir fiction]] / [[hardboiled]], and [[dark fantasy]] genres. He lived in Germany.\n\n== Work as author ==\nPulver started his publishing career in the early 1990s with a number of short stories published in various American [[small press]] magazines, foremost among them [[Robert M. Price]]'s ''Crypt of [[Cthulhu]]''. His tales cover subjects ranging from [[Robert Wiene]]'s ''[[The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari]]'' to [[H.P. Lovecraft]]'s [[Cthulhu Mythos]] and [[Robert W. Chambers]]' \"[[King in Yellow]].\"\n\nPulver's professional debut came with the publication of his [[Lovecraftian]] novel, \"[[Nightmare's Disciple]]\".\n\nIn addition to various American [[small press]] magazines ([[Hippocampus Press]], [[Lovecraft eZine]], [[Nemonymous]], etc.). Pulver's work has been featured in numerous [[anthologies]] in the US, UK, France, and Japan. Some of these [[anthologies]] include: \"Black Wings: New Tales of Lovecraftian Horror\", \"The Tindalos Mythos\", \"Spawn of the Green Abyss\", \"The Book of Eibon\", [[Lin Carter]]'s \"Anton Zarnak: Supernatural Sleuth\", and \"Rehearsals For Oblivion\".\n\nNearly two dozen short works of his have been translated into French and Japanese.\n\n== Work as editor ==\nPulver has also been the editor of [[Midnight Shambler]] and Tales of Lovecraftian Horror. He was also the co-editor for [[Crypt of Cthulhu]], published by Mythos Books LLC working alongside [[Robert M. Price]], [[Michael Cisco]] and David Wynn.\n\nHe has also edited collections by [[Ann K. Schwader]] (The Worms Remember, Hive Press) and John B. Ford (Dark Shadows on the Moon, Hive Press).\n\nIn 2012 Pulver edited ''A Season in Carcosa'' (an anthology of new tales based on [[Robert W. Chambers]]' \"[[The King in Yellow]]\" tales) for Miskatonic River Press. A year later he edited the award-winning anthology ''The Grimscribe's Puppets'' (a tribute anthology to [[Thomas Ligotti]] for the same publisher).\n\nMr. Pulver was guest editor for the [[Lovecraft eZine]] ''[[The King in Yellow]]'' special issue, which was published in April 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lovecraftzine.com/magazine/issues/2014-2/issue-30-april-2014/ |title=Introduction to Issue #30 |date=April 5, 2014 |website=lovecraftzine.com |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Cassilda's Song'' ([[Chaosium]]), an anthology based on [[Robert W. Chambers]]'s [[King in Yellow]] with new tales, written by female writers. The anthology has been released in 2015 in electronic format and will be available in print in the first quarter of 2016.\n\nFor the [[Necronomicon Providence]] Mr. Pulver edited a Round Robin for the Lovecraft Arts & Sciences Council, that included stories, artwork and accounts by participants of the [[Necronomicon Providence]] in 2013 and 2015.\n\nIn 2016 and 2017 several anthologies that have been edited by Joseph S. Pulver will be published. Amongst them are ''The Madness of Dr. Caligari'' ([[Fedogan & Bremer]], 2016), ''Darker Companions'' - a tribute to [[Ramsey Campbell]], co-edited with Scott David Aniolowski ([[PS Publishing]], 2016), ''Born under a Bad Sign'' and ''The Leaves of a Necronomicon'' ([[Chaosium]] in 2016/2017).\n\nMr. Pulver has curated the release of the [[Michael Cisco]] novella ''Knife Dance'' for Dim Shores. The novella will be published in 2016.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* 2013 [[Shirley Jackson Award]], as editor for Superior Work in an Anthology. ''The Grimscribe's Puppets'' ([[Miskatonic River Press]])\n* 2013 [[Bram Stoker Award]], Finalist for award in Superior Achievement in the Anthology Category. ''The Grimscribe's Puppets'' ([[Miskatonic River Press]])\n* 2016 [[World Fantasy Award]], Finalist for World Fantasy Award for Best Anthology. ''Cassilda's Song'' ([[Chaosium]])\n* 2016 [[Shirley Jackson Award]] nominee, for edited anthology. ''The Madness of Dr. Caligari'' ([[Fedogan & Bremer]])\n\n==Publications==\n===as editor===\n* ''The Worms remember'' by [[Ann K. Schwader]], Hive Press, 2001\n* ''Dark Shadows on the Moon'' by John B. Ford, Hive Press, 2001\n* ''A Season in Carcosa'', Miskatonic River Press, 2012\n* ''The Grimscribe's Puppets'', Miskatonic River Press, 2013\n* ''Cassilda's Song'', [[Chaosium]], 2015\n* ''The Doom that came to Providence'', The Lovecraft Arts & Sciences Council, 2015\n* ''Darker Companions'', [[PS Publishing]], co-edited with Scott D. Aniolowski, forthcoming in 2016\n* ''The Leaves of a Necronomicom'', [[Chaosium]], forthcoming in 2016\n* ''The Madness of Dr. Caligari'', [[Fedogan & Bremer]], forthcoming in 2016\n* ''Born under a Bad Sign'', [[Chaosium]], forthcoming in 2016/2017\n\n===Novels===\n* ''Nightmare's Disciple'', [[Chaosium]] 1999\n* ''The Orphan Palace'', [[Ch\u00f4mu Press]], October 2011\n\n===Collections===\n*''Blood Will Have Its Season'', edited by [[S.T. Joshi]], [[Hippocampus Press]] 2009\n*''SIN & ashes'', edited by [[S.T. Joshi]], [[Hippocampus Press]] 2010\n*''Portraits of Ruin'', [[Hippocampus Press]] 2012\n*''A House of Hollow Wounds'', edited by [[Jeffrey Thomas (writer)|Jeffrey Thomas]], [[Hippocampus Press]] 2015\n*''The Protocols of Ugliness'', (forthcoming) 2015\n*''The King in Yellow Tales, Vol. 1'', [[Lovecraft eZine]] books\n'''Graphic Novels'''\n* Knots, Gestures and Positions in [https://ashpure.com/outsideanthology/ Outside] An anthology of new horror fiction with artist Kim Bo Yung. Published by [https://ashpure.com/home/ Ash Pure] and Topic Press.\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[Anna Tambour]]: \"In human terms, if I had to compare him to other authors, I would say that he reminds me more of a mug of hot Lear blended with Cummings, served with a squeeze of post-enema'd Shelley.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://medlarcomfits.blogspot.com.au/ |first=Anna |last=Tambour |title=upcoming in A Season in Carcosa, editor: Joseph S. Pulver Sr. |date=January 24, 2012 |website=Medlar Comfits |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===''Blood Will Have Its Season''===\n\"The prose of Joe Pulver can take its place with that of the masters of our genre-Poe, Lovecraft, Campbell, Ligotti-while his imaginative reach is something uniquely his own.\" \u2014 From [[S. T. Joshi]]'s Foreword.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.blood\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/blood-will-have-its-season-by-joseph-s.-pulver-sr |title=Blood Will Have Its Season by Joseph S. Pulver Sr |first=Boyd |last=Pearson |website=Hippocampus Press |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"In this innovative, hypnotic collection, Joseph S. Pulver Sr. has proven himself to be a perversely masterful sculptor of our dreams.\"-Jeffrey Thomas.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.blood\"/>\n\n\"Joe Pulver is a dark star in the merciless cosmos of weird fiction. His work is as brutal as it is beautiful.\" \u2014 [[Wilum Pugmire]].<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.blood\"/>\n\n\"In an earlier day I feel sure Joe Pulver would have been arrested for writing some of the stuff in this collection. Maybe he will be yet! How can he write, with such intricate delicacy, thunderous prose that fairly rips up the pages it is printed on? I wish I knew!\" \u2014 [[Robert M. Price]].<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.blood\"/>\n\n===''The Grimscribe's Puppets''===\n\"[[Thomas Ligotti]] is beyond doubt one of the Grandmasters of Weird Fiction. In The Grimscribe's Puppets, Joseph S. Pulver Sr. has commissioned both new and established talents in the world of weird fiction and horror to contribute all new tales that pay homage to Ligotti and celebrate his eerie and essential nightmares. [[Poppy Z. Brite]] once asked, \"Are you out there, Thomas Ligotti?\" This anthology proves not only is he alive and well, but his extraordinary illuminations have proven to be a visionary and fertile source of inspiration for some of today's most accomplished authors.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.miskatonicriverpress.com/products/gp.shtml |title=The Grimscribe's Puppets edited by Joseph S. Pulver Sr. |website=Miskatonic River Press |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310213923/http://www.miskatonicriverpress.com/products/gp.shtml |archivedate=March 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''The Orphan Palace''===\n[[Maureen Kincaid Speller]] for ''Weird Fiction Review'': \"Moving to the present day, ''The Orphan Palace'' by Joseph S. Pulver (Ch\u00f4mu Press, 2011) certainly cannot be accused of such reticence. Ostensibly, the story of a road trip made by a serial arsonist and killer, from the West Coast to the East, in search of his childhood nemesis is not promising material, and I don't mind admitting that The Orphan Palace initially seemed to sit far out on the edge of my reading comfort zone. However, it quickly became clear that there is much more to this novel than a trail of dumped cars, torched buildings and broken and bloody bodies.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://weirdfictionreview.com/2012/03/the-mere-touch-weird-reviews/ |title=The Mere Touch: Weird Reviews |first=Maureen Kincaid |last=Speller |work=Weird Fiction Review |date=March 16, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===''Portraits of Ruin''===\n[[Matt Cardin]]: \"Just be prepared for a ride that will upend your sensibilities. [...] Portraits of Ruin truly is a Coney Island of the Mind. But it's one where the rides drip with darkness and tilt at non-Euclidean angles, and whirl you into an abyss of strange entity that grins and chitters and babbles in alien tongues (which eventually come to sound like your own voice).\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teemingbrain.com/2012/03/26/on-learning-to-read-joe-pulvers-portraits-of-ruin-by-writing-the-introduction-to-it/ |first=Matt |last=Cardin |title=On learning to read Joe Pulver\u2019s \u2018Portraits of Ruin\u2019 by writing the introduction to it |date=March 26, 2012 |website=The Teeming Brain |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Let us posit that Bukowski is the sun. Or Brautigan, Burroughs and the Beats\u2014a solar Coney Island of the Mind where Timothy Leary's dead and dead Cthulhu waits and sings the live long daydream believer. Then Joe Pulver's Portraits of Ruin would be the burst of planets, Big Bang-Bang, Marquee Moons hanging on for what they got, scream of consciousness\u2014in Outer Space no one can hear it . . . except Coffin Joe, Monster Mash Potato that big ol' Portraits of Ruin\u2014Mars needs it, you need it, so just open the lid and shake your fist\u2014then say: \"They kill horses, horses, horses, horses.\" Thank you. Come again?\" \u2014Thomas Ligotti.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.portraits\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/portraits-of-ruin |title=Portraits of Ruin by Joseph S. Pulver Sr. |first=Boyd |last=Pearson |website=Hippocampus Press |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Fearless. Daring. Poetic prose for the unhinged. Each tale in Portraits of Ruin packs the sort of mental wallop that leaves the reader reeling. From the scorched deserts to the highest foreign towers, across plains of reality and beneath burning suns, this is no volume for the weak, for the conventional. It is a wake-up call from one of the genre's most visionary masters. A book for those who see differently, for those not afraid to know the truth no matter how terrible the cost. I envy anyone about to experience Pulver's horrors for the first time.\" \u2013 [[Simon Strantzas]], author of ''Nightingale Songs''.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.portraits\"/>\n\n===''A Season in Carcosa''===\n[[Nic Pizzolatto]], the creator of ''[[True Detective (TV series)|True Detective]]'', refers to ''A Season in Carcosa'' in a recent interview with ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/02/02/writer-nic-pizzolatto-on-thomas-ligotti-and-the-weird-secrets-of-true-detective/ |title=Writer Nic Pizzolatto on Thomas Ligotti and the Weird Secrets of 'True Detective' |first=Michael |last=Calia |date=February 2, 2014 |journal=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> \"For fans of the show who'd like to see what contemporary voices have done with Chambers' \"King in Yellow,\" I'd point them toward Karl Edward Wagner's short story \"The River of Night's Dreaming\" or the recent anthology \"A Season in Carcosa.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/5-things-we-learned-from-true-detective-20140310 |title=5 Things We Learned From 'True Detective' |first=David |last=Fear |date=March 10, 2014 |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Walter Hicks]] (Hellbound Times): \"This is a superior collection, with a diverse and outstanding line-up of talent. As with any anthology, some of the stories will work better for individual readers than others, but each one merits inclusion and consideration here. Does it accentuate the reading experience to be familiar with Chambers/The King in Yellow? Probably, and though I would highly recommend reading the source material, it certainly is not a necessity. All readers who enjoy ominous, enigmatic and darkly beautiful literature, highly imaginative journeys into madness, altered realities and the true terror behind the Mask will relish spending A Season in Carcosa.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Season-Carcosa-Sr-Joseph-Pulver/dp/1937408000/ref=wl_it_dp_o_pdT1_nS_nC?ie=UTF8&colid=2F4V4U3J4GAY8&coliid=I2K4OSCSYV1Q9D |title=A Season in Carcosa |editor-first=Joseph S. |editor-last=Pulver Sr. |date=September 15, 2012 |publisher=Miskatonic River Press, LLC |accessdate=June 15, 2017 |via=Amazon}}</ref>\n\n===SIN & ashes===\nLaird Barron in SF Signal: \"Joe Pulver's Sin & Ashes is a hardboiled/noir/horror collection that reads like prose poetry; a psychedelic hybrid of James Ellroy, William Burroughs, and H.P. Lovecraft. It'll rattle your brain.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sfsignal.com/archives/2010/12/be-my-victim-laird-barron |title=Be My Victim: A Discussion with Laird Barron on Literary Horror and Anti-Intellectualism |work=SF Signal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013093326/http://www.sfsignal.com/archives/2010/12/be-my-victim-laird-barron/ |archivedate=October 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"Joseph S Pulver Sr. is a thunderous scribe of dark fiction. His poetry slams into you, cracking through flesh and bone to the real meat beneath. SIN & ashes is his mighty hammer, deftly wielded and smithed on Hephaestus's great anvil. This is no book for the faint of heart. Filled with hard boiled goodness and devastating imagery, Pulver proves his is a talent to be reckoned with, and cements his rightful place as one of the most interesting voices in the genre. I am both awed and humbled by his power.\" \u2014 Simon Strantzas.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.portraits\"/>\n\n\"Joe Pulver's ''Sins and Ashes'' is a messed up (and I mean Cronenberg messed up) splicing of William S. Burroughs and Thomas Ligotti. Add a whiskey chaser. After reading these vibrant and weird stories with their assorted devils and down-and-outs, I kinda want to party with Joe. But I think I'm too scared to.\" \u2014 Paul Tremblay, author of The Little Sleep and in the Mean Time.<ref name=\"hippocampuspress.portraits\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{isfdb name}}\n*{{facebook|jspulver}}\n*[http://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/sin-ashes-by-joseph-s.-pulver-sr. \"SIN & ashes\" at Hippocampus Press]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pulver, Joseph S. Sr.}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cthulhu Mythos writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American book editors]]\n[[Category:American horror writers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Berlin]]\n[[Category:American male short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Weird fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Schenectady, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Sharth", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_S._Pulver_Sr."}
{"title_page": "Luke Dean (footballer, born 1991)", "text_new": "{{for|the forward who played for Port Vale and Northwich Victoria|Luke Dean (footballer, born 1913)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Luke Dean\n| image =\n| fullname = Luke Adam Dean<ref name=\"List of Players under Written Contract Registered Between 1\u201331 August 2010\">{{cite web\n| title = List of Players under Written Contract Registered Between 01/08/2010 and 31/08/2010\n| url = http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/RulesandRegulations/~/media/Files/PDF/TheFA/PlayerRegistrations/August%202010.ashx/August%202010.pdf\n| publisher = The Football Association\n| format = PDF\n| accessdate = 14 October 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1991|5|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cleckheaton]],<ref>{{cite book|editor1-first=Glenda|editor1-last=Rollin|editor2-first=Jack|editor2-last=Rollin|title=Sky Sports Football Yearbook 2012\u20132013|year=2012|publisher=[[Headline Publishing Group|Headline]]|location=London|isbn=978-0-7553-6356-8|page=437|edition=43rd}}</ref> England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| currentclub = [[Matlock Town F.C.|Matlock Town]]\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 2002\u20132009 | youthclubs1 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| years1 = 2009\u20132012 | clubs1 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]            | caps1 = 3 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2009      | clubs2 = \u2192 [[F.C. Halifax Town|Halifax Town]] (loan)       | caps2 = 1 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2011      | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Ossett Town F.C.|Ossett Town]] (loan)         | caps3 = 2 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2011      | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Hinckley United F.C.|Hinckley United]] (loan) | caps4 = 7 | goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2011      | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Harrogate Town F.C.|Harrogate Town]] (loan)   | caps5 = 4 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2012      | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Harrogate Town F.C.|Harrogate Town]] (loan)   | caps6 = 6 | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2012\u20132013 | clubs7 =  [[Harrogate Town F.C.|Harrogate Town]]           | caps7 = 26| goals7 = 5 \n| years8 = 2013      | clubs8 = [[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]]| caps8 = 1 |goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs9 = [[Workington A.F.C.|Workington]] | caps9 = 3 | goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs10 = [[Harrogate Town F.C.|Harrogate Town]] | caps10 = 4 | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2015 | clubs11 = \u2192 [[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]] (loan) | caps11 = 19 | goals11 = 1\n| years12 = 2015\u20132017 | clubs12 = [[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]] | caps12 = 60 | goals12 = 4\n| years13 = 2017\u20132019 | clubs13 = [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] | caps13 =  | goals13 = \n| years14 = 2019\u2013 | clubs14 = [[Matlock Town F.C.|Matlock Town]] | caps14 = 0 | goals14 = 0\n| club-update = 11 June 2017 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Luke Adam  Dean''' (born 14 May 1991) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Matlock Town F.C.|Matlock Town]].\n \n==Career==\nDean joined Bradford City's centre of excellence in 2002.<ref name=\"race against the clock\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/8414013.Bradford_City_midfielder_Dean_faces_a_race_against_the_clock/ |title=Bradford City midfielder Dean faces a race against the clock |date=25 September 2010 |accessdate=25 September 2010 |newspaper=Telegraph & Argus |first=Simon |last=Parker}}</ref> He made his club debut against [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]] on 13 April 2010.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}  becoming the first Asian home grown player to make his debut as a professional for Bradford City. He rewarded with a contract on 16 June 2010<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/bantams_heck/8100067.Younger_lads_have_not_let_anyone_down/|title=Younger lads have not let anyone down|last=Bullock|first=Lee|date=15 April 2010|work=Bradford Telegraph and Argus|accessdate=17 April 2010}}</ref> but suffered a setback when he broke his leg in a pre-season friendly.<ref name=\"race against the clock\"/>\n\nDean moved to [[Ossett Town F.C.|Ossett Town]] on loan in March 2011 but was recalled a month later by new Bradford City manager Peter Jackson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/page/News/0,,10266~2319044,00.html|title=Dean joins Ossett on loan|accessdate=18 March 2011|date=18 March 2011|publisher=Bradford City A.F.C.}}</ref> Luke Dean was the only player of the 2011 Bradford City out of contract players to be handed a new contract, which would keep him at the club until at least June 2012.\n\nIn August 2011, he joined [[Hinckley United F.C.|Hinckley United]] on a month-long loan deal, alongside [[Darren Stephenson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/9213712.Bradford_City_duo_go_on_loan/|title=Bradford City duo go on loan|accessdate=24 August 2011|date=24 August 2011|author=Simon Parker|publisher=Telegraph and Argus}}</ref> In May 2012, Dean was released from Bradford .<ref>[http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12691/7751048/Bantams-clear-out-gets-underway Bantams clear-out gets underway] Skysports, 12 May 2012. Retrieved on 12 May 2012.</ref> He signed for [[Harrogate Town F.C.|Harrogate Town]] of the [[Conference North]] in the summer of 2012.\n\nIn January 2015, Dean signed a one-month loan deal for [[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tc1.bpafc.com/avenue-make-triple-signing/|title=Avenue make triple signing|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=[[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112215539/http://tc1.bpafc.com/avenue-make-triple-signing/|archive-date=12 January 2015|url-status=dead}}.</ref> In February 2015, [[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]] and [[Harrogate Town F.C.|Harrogate Town]] agreed to extend the loan deal until the end of the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tc1.bpafc.com/lukes-loan-extended/|title=Luke's Loan Extended|publisher=[[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]]|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nDean joined [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] on 25 May 2017.<ref>[http://www.scarboroughathletic.com/news/2017-05-25/luke-dean-ready-for-new-challenge-at-boro LUKE DEAN READY FOR NEW CHALLENGE AT BORO]\u201a scarboroughathletic.com, 25 May 2017</ref> He played for the club until May 2019, where he signed with [[Matlock Town F.C.|Matlock Town]].<ref>[http://www.evostikleague.co.uk/kittrick-makes-first-signings-at-matlock-57124 Kittrick makes first signings at Matlock], evostikleague.co.uk, 28 May 2019</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{Soccerway|luke-dean/85256}}\n*[http://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10266~47687,00.html Bradford City A.F.C. official profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dean, Luke}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cleckheaton]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:F.C. Halifax Town players]]\n[[Category:Ossett Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hinckley United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Harrogate Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford (Park Avenue) A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Workington A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Northern Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Scarborough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Matlock Town F.C. players]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-midfielder-1990s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the forward who played for Port Vale and Northwich Victoria|Luke Dean (footballer, born 1913)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Luke Dean\n| image =\n| fullname = Luke Adam Dean<ref name=\"List of 